# ADR-002: Clean Architecture

**Status**

Accepted

**Date**

2026-06-30

**Authors**

Healthcare Platform Team

---

# Context

Healthcare Platform is a long-term enterprise application composed of multiple independently deployable microservices.

The platform is expected to evolve continuously while maintaining high maintainability, testability, scalability and technology independence.

Each microservice will implement business capabilities such as Authentication, Identity Management, Appointment Scheduling, Medical Records, Pharmacy and Billing.

To avoid tight coupling between business logic and technical frameworks, the project requires an architectural style that clearly separates business rules from infrastructure concerns.

---

# Decision Drivers

The selected architecture must satisfy the following quality attributes:

* High maintainability
* High testability
* Technology independence
* Framework independence
* Database independence
* Low coupling
* High cohesion
* Scalability
* Long-term maintainability
* Ease of onboarding new developers

---

# Options Considered

## Layered Architecture (N-Tier)

### Advantages

* Simple to understand
* Widely adopted
* Easy to start

### Disadvantages

* Business logic often leaks into controllers or persistence layers.
* Strong dependency on frameworks.
* Difficult to unit test in isolation.
* High coupling between layers.

---

## Hexagonal Architecture

### Advantages

* Excellent separation of concerns.
* Infrastructure independence.
* Easy to replace adapters.
* Highly testable.

### Disadvantages

* Does not explicitly organize application use cases.
* Requires additional conventions to structure complex domains.

---

## Onion Architecture

### Advantages

* Strong dependency inversion.
* Domain-centric design.
* Technology independence.

### Disadvantages

* Less standardized across teams.
* Can become difficult to organize as the project grows.

---

## Clean Architecture

### Advantages

* Clear separation between business rules and infrastructure.
* Explicit application use cases.
* Strong dependency inversion.
* Highly testable.
* Framework agnostic.
* Easy to evolve.
* Excellent fit for Domain-Driven Design.

### Disadvantages

* More initial boilerplate.
* Additional abstractions.
* Requires architectural discipline.

---

# Decision

Healthcare Platform will adopt **Clean Architecture** as the standard architecture for every microservice.

Business rules will always remain independent from:

* Spring Boot
* Databases
* Messaging systems
* REST controllers
* Security frameworks
* External APIs

Frameworks and technologies are considered implementation details.

Business logic must never depend directly on infrastructure.

---

# Architecture

Each microservice will follow the same internal structure.

```text
                 REST API
                     │
              Controllers
                     │
             Application Layer
             (Use Cases)
                     │
              Domain Layer
     (Entities, Value Objects,
      Domain Services, Ports)
                     │
         Infrastructure Layer
(PostgreSQL, JWT, RabbitMQ, REST,
 Flyway, Spring Security)
```

Dependencies always point inward.

The Domain Layer has no dependencies on any external framework.

---

# Package Structure

Every microservice must follow the same package organization.

```text
src/main/java
└── com.healthcare.platform.auth
    ├── application
    │   ├── ports
    │   └── usecase
    │
    ├── domain
    │   ├── model
    │   ├── service
    │   ├── valueobject
    │   └── exception
    │
    ├── infrastructure
    │   ├── configuration
    │   ├── persistence
    │   ├── security
    │   ├── messaging
    │   └── client
    │
    └── entrypoint
        ├── rest
        ├── dto
        └── mapper
```

This package structure is mandatory for every microservice.

---

# Dependency Rule

The Dependency Rule is the fundamental principle of this architecture.

Dependencies must always point toward the domain.

Allowed direction:

```text
Controller
      ↓
Use Case
      ↓
Domain
```

Infrastructure implements interfaces defined by the application or domain.

The domain never imports infrastructure classes.

---

# Testing Strategy

Each architectural layer must be tested independently.

* Domain: Unit Tests only
* Application: Unit Tests with mocked ports
* Infrastructure: Integration Tests
* REST Controllers: API Tests

Business rules must be executable without starting Spring Boot.

---

# Benefits

Adopting Clean Architecture provides:

* Framework independence
* Easier testing
* Better maintainability
* Better readability
* Lower coupling
* Better scalability
* Easier replacement of technologies
* Clear separation of responsibilities

---

# Consequences

Positive:

* Consistent architecture across all services.
* Easier onboarding.
* High code quality.
* Better long-term maintainability.
* Simplified automated testing.

Negative:

* More project structure.
* More interfaces.
* Slightly higher learning curve.
* More initial development effort.

---

# Trade-offs

The project intentionally accepts additional architectural complexity in exchange for long-term maintainability and technology independence.

Although small CRUD applications may not require this level of abstraction, Healthcare Platform is expected to evolve into a large enterprise ecosystem where these architectural boundaries provide significant long-term value.

---

# Future Considerations

Future services may introduce:

* CQRS
* Event Sourcing
* Saga Pattern
* Outbox Pattern

These patterns must integrate without violating the Clean Architecture dependency rules defined in this ADR.

